	<div class="entry-content p402_premium">
				<figure class="align-none wp-caption post-img" id="post-352830media-352830" itemprop="image" itemscope itemid="http://wcmimages.leaderpost.com/images?url=https://postmedialeaderpost2.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/close-up-of-a-medical-history-form-and-a-doctors-stethoscope.jpeg&#038;w=840&#038;h=630" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject">
			<img class="wp-post-image" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="840" height="630" />
			<meta itemprop="url" content="http://wcmimages.leaderpost.com/images?url=https://postmedialeaderpost2.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/close-up-of-a-medical-history-form-and-a-doctors-stethoscope.jpeg&#038;w=840&#038;h=630">
			<meta itemprop="width" content="840">
			<meta itemprop="height" content="630">
							<figcaption class="wp-caption-text" itemprop="description">
					<p><span class="img-caption">
						A Regina doctor was penalized more than $10,000 for his response to a family concerned he had botched their son&#039;s circumcision.</span>
						<span class="img-author">
							<span itemprop="creator">Chad McDermott</span> / <span itemprop="copyrightHolder">Chad McDermott - Fotolia</span>						</span>
					</p>
				</figcaption>
						</figure>
				<div class="article-actions">
			<a href="#" class="icon-share" data-modal-target="#modal-share">Share</a>
			<a href="#" class="icon-adjust">Adjust</a>
			<a href="#" class="icon-comment">Comment</a>
			<a href="javascript:window.print();" class="icon-print">Print</a>
		</div>
		<div itemprop="articleBody">
			<p>A Regina doctor has been ordered to pay more than $10,000 after a circumcision went wrong and then, according to the province&rsquo;s medical college, he &ldquo;misadvised&rdquo; parents by claiming everything was fine.</p><p>The boy later required &ldquo;significant corrective surgery&rdquo; to repair the mistake.</p><p>In April 2014, Dr. Zimran Chowdhary circumcised the infant, referred to only as &ldquo;J.T.&rdquo; in a decision from the College of Physicians and Surgeons of Saskatchewan. In the decision published last week, the college said&nbsp; he &ldquo;failed to deal appropriately with the complications associated with the surgery.&rdquo;</p><p>The college did not reveal exactly what the complications involved, but they quoted a memo from Chowdhary to another doctor where he stated the parents were concerned that skin had fused to the head of J.T.&rsquo;s penis.</p><p>Bryan Salte, associate registrar of the college, told the Leader-Post the boy was born with &ldquo;abnormalities&rdquo; which caused the complications. He said that a circumcision should not have been performed in the first place.</p><p>When reached for comment, Chowdhary confirmed that anatomical differences were at the root of the problem.</p><p>Salte said the error could have easily been made by other physicians. The issue was the way Chowdhary dealt with his mistake.</p><p>The parents became worried about the complications, and took their son to another physician, who expressed &ldquo;concerns&rdquo; about the circumcision. The parents then returned J.T. to Chowdhary for another consultation in October 2014.</p><p>The doctor denied that there had been any mistake. He claimed that the condition was normal and noted that the circumcision appeared to have healed well.</p><p>&ldquo;Following your examination of J.T. you advised his parents that J.T. would grow out his condition and that no further surgery would be needed, or used words of similar meaning,&rdquo; the college said.</p><p>All of this was inaccurate, according to Salte.</p><p>&ldquo;It needed corrective surgery and there was a fairly significant amount of corrective surgery that was required,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Based upon our information, misadvising the parents about the concerns was the nature of the charge.&rdquo;</p><p>Chowdhary admitted to the charges of unprofessional conduct related to the case.</p><p>On March 16, the college formally reprimanded Chowdhary and ordered him to pay the full costs of the investigation and hearing. That totalled $10,051.</p><p>But Chowdhary continues to maintain that he was unaware of the problem when he provided inaccurate information to the parents in October. Salte said it&rsquo;s difficult to determine whether he misled the parents knowingly or unknowingly.</p><p>&ldquo;Thats always a difficult thing, when wrong information has been given. Is it wrong information because someone was careless? Is it wrong information because it&rsquo;s covering up?&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Or is it wrong information for some other reason.&rdquo;</p><p>Chowdhary strongly denied that he misinformed the parents intentionally.</p><p>&ldquo;It wasn&rsquo;t covering up the mistake, no,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;It was just that I didn&rsquo;t recognize it at the time.&rdquo;</p><p><a href="mailto:awhite-crummey@postmedia.com">awhite-crummey@postmedia.com</a></p>		</div>
